TY  - JOUR
T1  - When Does Scientist Recruitment Affect Technological Repositioning?
AU  - Tzabbar, Daniel
Y1  - 2009/10/01
PY  - 2009
DA  - 2009/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2009.44632853
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2009.44632853
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 873
EP  - 896
VL  - 52
IS  - 5
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - An investigation of the conditions in which the recruitment of technologically distant scientists results in a significant technological repositioning reveals, on the basis of 2,643 biotechnology industry hiring events between 1973 and 1999, that recruitment is positively associated with repositioning. However, the more a firm's innovative productivity depends on one or a few ?star? scientists, the less likely it is that recruitment affects repositioning. This likelihood increases at moderate levels of technological breadth and declines at very high or low levels. These results offer insights into the challenges of developing combinative capabilities by hiring scientific personnel.
AB  - An investigation of the conditions in which the recruitment of technologically distant scientists results in a significant technological repositioning reveals, on the basis of 2,643 biotechnology industry hiring events between 1973 and 1999, that recruitment is positively associated with repositioning. However, the more a firm's innovative productivity depends on one or a few ?star? scientists, the less likely it is that recruitment affects repositioning. This likelihood increases at moderate levels of technological breadth and declines at very high or low levels. These results offer insights into the challenges of developing combinative capabilities by hiring scientific personnel.
