TY  - JOUR
T1  - Bosses' Perceptions of Family-Work Conflict and Women's Promotability: Glass Ceiling Effects
AU  - Hoobler, Jenny M.
AU  - Wayne, Sandy J.
AU  - Lemmon, Grace
Y1  - 2009/10/01
PY  - 2009
DA  - 2009/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2009.44633700
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2009.44633700
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 939
EP  - 957
VL  - 52
IS  - 5
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We examine one potential reason for the persistence of the glass ceiling: bosses' perceptions of female subordinates' family-work conflict. Person categorization and social role theories are used to examine whether bosses (both male and female) perceive women as having greater family-work conflict and therefore view them as mismatched to their organizations and jobs. The results support our model: bosses' perceptions of family-work conflict mediated the relationships between subordinate sex and perceptions of person-organization fit, person-job fit, and performance. Both types of fit were related to promotability (nomination for promotion and manager-assessed promotability). We discuss implications for practice and future research.
AB  - We examine one potential reason for the persistence of the glass ceiling: bosses' perceptions of female subordinates' family-work conflict. Person categorization and social role theories are used to examine whether bosses (both male and female) perceive women as having greater family-work conflict and therefore view them as mismatched to their organizations and jobs. The results support our model: bosses' perceptions of family-work conflict mediated the relationships between subordinate sex and perceptions of person-organization fit, person-job fit, and performance. Both types of fit were related to promotability (nomination for promotion and manager-assessed promotability). We discuss implications for practice and future research.
